{
  "texts": [
    "A value of 0 for MI(A, B|S) indicates that there is no information flow between A and B when conditioned onS, that is, they are conditionally independent.",
    "In practice a threshold value is chosen so that if MI(A, B|S) < 𝜖, conditional independence is assumed.",
    "Variable may be given an arbitrary small value such as 0.01 (Cheng et al. 1997) or it may be estimated by comparing the predictive accuracy using different values (Cheng and Greiner 1999).",
    "If we rewrite the frequencies used in the definition of the G 2 test statistic as probabilities, we see that it only differs from mutual information by a scaling factor:",
    "In the case of Gaussian BNs, Fisher's Z-test is commonly used to test the null hypothesis that the partial correlation coefficient is zero."
  ]
}